    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Wait, a \"goblin in the attic\"? That's an odd way to put it. Anyway, regarding point 2, since this is an embedded automotive environment, we have very limited overhead. Valgrind might be too heavy for our actual hardware. How would you refine that custom tracker idea for a resource-constrained system?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Fair point about the \"goblin in the attic\" analogy. I guess I was just trying to add a bit of whimsy to the situation.\n\nFor a resource-constrained embedded system, you're right that Valgrind might be too heavy. A custom memory tracker can be implemented using a simple, lightweight approach. Here's a refined idea:\n\n1. **Use a static array to track allocations**: Create a static array of a fixed size (e.g., 1024 elements) to keep track of memory allocations. Each time you allocate memory, increment the corresponding index in the array. When you deallocate memory, decrement the index. If the index goes below 0, it indicates a leak.\n2. **Use a bit flag to indicate allocation status**: Since you have limited overhead, you can use a single bit flag to indicate whether a memory allocation is valid or not. When you allocate memory, set the corresponding bit to 1. When you deallocate memory, set the bit to 0. This way, you can quickly check if a memory allocation is still valid.\n3. **Use a circular buffer to handle large allocations**: If you need to allocate large blocks of memory, you can use a circular buffer to handle them",
      "source": "target",
